  "prompt": "What is the difference between angular velocity and angular acceleration?",
  "response": "Let me explain the difference between angular velocity and angular acceleration:\n\nAngular Velocity:\n1. Measures the rate of rotation of an object\n2. Describes how quickly an object is spinning\n3. Represented by \u03c9 (omega)\n4. Units are typically radians per second (rad/s)\n5. Constant direction of rotation\n6. Tells you how many rotations an object makes in a given time\n\nAngular Acceleration:\n1. Measures the rate of change of angular velocity\n2. Describes how quickly the rotational speed is changing\n3. Represented by \u03b1 (alpha)\n4. Units are typically radians per second squared (rad/s\u00b2)\n5. Indicates whether rotation is speeding up or slowing down\n6. Shows how the angular velocity is changing over time\n\nExample:\n- If a bicycle wheel is spinning at a constant rate of 10 rad/s, its angular velocity is 10 rad/s\n- If the wheel is speeding up or slowing down, changing its angular velocity, that change represents angular acceleration\n\nIn mathematical terms:\n- Angular velocity (\u03c9) is the derivative of angular displacement\n- Angular acceleration (\u03b1) is the derivative of angular velocity",
